[1] Malaysia (National)
Date: 21 Dec 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Star Online [edited]
<http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2006/12/21/central/16370055&sec=central>

As of 9 Dec [2006], there were 34 386 cases of dengue reported nationwide.
Of the figure, there were 13 deaths. "In Kuala Lumpur and Putrajaya alone,
there were 6644 cases," said Deputy Federal Territories Minister Datuk Wira
Abu Seman Yusop at the launch of the Lifelong Health Carnival 2006 (Federal
Territories level) recently.
He said efforts had been made by the Federal Territories and City Hall
health departments to curb the menace, especially at crowded residential
areas. Among the plans is the Communication for Behavioral Impact (COMBI)
program. However, Abu Seman said the public ought to seek treatment fast if
they suspected that they had caught dengue fever.
Kuala Lumpur health department director E.G. Palaniyappan said the COMBI
program had been introduced at 3 zones: Setapak, Klang Lama and Kuala
Lumpur city center. "We hope more people from more zones will form
committees to begin the program," he said at the launch.
[Byline Christina Low]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
