[2] Malaysia (Selangor)
Date: 21 Dec 2006
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: The Star Online [edited]
<http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2006/12/21/central/16356487&sec=central>

The number of dengue cases in Selangor has gone above 11 000 so far this
year [2006], and the State Government is unhappy over the statistics.
State Health Committee chairman Datuk Dr Lim Thuang Seng said he was
disappointed that the number exceeded the state's target of keeping the
cases below 11 000.
"Last year [2005], there were 12 700 cases, and our efforts to keep the
numbers low did not work," he said. "This is because the state government
lacked the cooperation and support from the public."
Lim said the difference in the number between 2005 and this year [2006] was
insignificant. "By the end of the year, it may surpass the 12 000 mark. We
have done everything possible, including holding anti-dengue campaigns and
carrying out fogging exercises, but the people failed to take precautionary
measures," he said after distributing free abate and flyers to motorists at
the LDP toll plaza in Bandar Sunway on Monday [18 Dec 2006].
A total of 4000 packets of abates, a contribution from BASF (M) Sdn Bhd,
were distributed at the Batu Tiga toll plaza along the Kuala Lumpur-Klang
Federal Highway. Some were distributed at the toll plaza in front of the
Eastin Hotel, along the Sprint Highway.
"Without the support from the public, the state's efforts would simply be a
waste," said Lim. "They must do their part, and they must do it earnestly,"
he said, adding that the public should destroy all mosquito breeding
grounds near their homes and compounds. "We have been educating the public
on this, but they don't seem to have learnt their lesson. Hopefully, their
mind sets will change soon."
Subang Jaya Municipal Council, Shah Alam City Council and Kajang Municipal
Council recorded the highest number of cases in the Klang Valley last week,
with 54 cases each. Gombak district had 43 cases, followed by 36 recorded
by the Petaling Jaya City Council.
"We hope those who are going for the year-end holidays will ensure that
their homes are free from mosquito breeding spots," said Dr Lim.
[Byline Elan Perumal]
